Summary:

“No.” Steve says as his eyes fall upon the very soul that stole Steve’s yarn, the man who has now upset Steve from his spot as a first place winner, standing next to the pieces that beat Steve’s. “It was him.” He says, raising one accusing finger to point in the direction of James Buchanan Barnes, now a thief of both yarn and dignity.

In which Bucky is Steve’s knitting nemesis and very little actual knitting occurs.

title: Movie Review...Ant-Man and The Wasp
body: (3/5) Just as entertaining as the first…no real improvements from the first though. Very simple story and character in my opinion. There is just nothing overly interesting about Ant-Man and his adventures.  Lighthearted and simply down the middle in all aspects from action, to plot and comedy. Great for kids not so much for people like me who prefer a heavier tone.  From the Marvel Cinematic Universe comes a new chapter featuring heroes with the astonishing ability to shrink: “Ant-Man and The Wasp.” In the aftermath of “Captain America: Civil War,” Scott Lang (Rudd) grapples with the consequences of his choices as both a Super Hero and a father. As he struggles to rebalance his home life with his responsibilities as Ant-Man, he’s confronted by Hope van Dyne (Lilly) and Dr. Hank Pym (Douglas) with an urgent new mission. Scott must once again put on the suit and learn to fight alongside The Wasp as the team works together to uncover secrets from their past (rottentomatoes.com).
